We recommended that the Local Chief Executive direct:

The Municipal Budget Officer to prepare monthly/quarterly SAAOB to ensure accurate declaration of savings as source of fund for supplemental budgets;
The Municipal Accountant to:
Request for additional manpower in order to augment the much-needed staff and avoid bottlenecks in the preparation of important financial reports;
Prepare and submit monthly/quarterly financial reports, including trial balances, interim financial statements, and quarterly utilization reports, to COA.
We also recommended the Local Chief Executive to consider the installation of eNGAS to facilitate the timely preparation of financial reports and ensure correctness, reliability, completeness and timeliness in recognizing government financial transactions.

We further recommended that the Local Chief Executive instruct the Municipal Treasurer to fortify financial management on cash receipts by strictly supervising the daily remittance and deposit of collections through the following measures:

Inform all collecting officers to properly prepare their individual Report on Collections and Deposits (RCDs), with the Abstract of Receipts supported by the issued ORs upon remittance of their collections;
Designate a Liquidating Officer who will oversee the punctual reporting and strict cut-off of daily remittances from all collecting officers to prevent theft/loss, misuse, and misappropriation of cash in their possession and ensure that a chronological system is implemented for the issuance of Official Receipts;
Refrain from using collections in augmenting cash advances for operating expenses and for using the same for other purposes (i.e. grant of IOUs to officials and employees).
We further recommended that the Local Chief Executive instruct the Municipal Treasurer to ensure that remittances are deposited intact daily or on the next banking day to safeguard the fund from possible loss, misuse, or misappropriation and to ensure the availability of cash for its immediate use to implement essential PPAs.
Lastly, direct the Municipal Accountant and the Municipal Treasurer to update their records on time in order to facilitate reconciliation between the cashbook and accounting records.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive direct the Municipal Treasurer to:

Eliminate the practice of granting cash advances lumpsum purpose by separating cash advances for specific activities such as payment of salaries and wages of Job Orders, labor payroll and other operating activities;
Initiate a formal request to the Sangguniang Bayan for authorization to establish a dedicated fund for the AICS based on previous year’s transactions;
Designate separate special disbursing officers for the payment of AICS and labor payroll for development activities of the agency to reduce the work responsibility of the Municipal Treasurer; and
Enforce a policy where transactions exceeding the ₱15,000.00 threshold are settled via checks, except in cases where check payments are exceptionally difficult, impractical, or impossible.
We also recommended that the Local Chief Executive direct the Municipal Accountant to ensure compliance with COA Circular No. 97-002 on the granting, utilization and liquidation of cash advances particularly, and attach complete supporting documents for the liquidation reports.
Further, we recommended that the Local Chief Executive to direct the BAC to implement stricter procurement process for transactions involving meals and snacks and other supplies by ensuring that canvass from at least three suppliers for purchases exceeding ₱2,000.00 to ensure competitive pricing. Relative thereto, the BAC to consider the use of Framework Agreement in the procurement of meals and snacks pursuant to Appendix 32 of 2016 Revised Implementing Rules and Regulations (IRR) of RA No. 9184;

